1
00:00:04,150 --> 00:00:09,670
The Doppler-Fizeau is one of the most invaluable
tools in astrophysics.

2
00:00:09,670 --> 00:00:12,910
It allows a direct measurement of the velocity
of stellar objects

3
00:00:12,910 --> 00:00:17,881
and so enables the study of their movement.
When used along with the Viriel theorem or

4
00:00:17,881 --> 00:00:22,910
the Kepler's laws,
both bringing in the velocities,

5
00:00:22,910 --> 00:00:27,679
it also allows indirect measurement of the
masses of celestial bodies.

6
00:00:27,679 --> 00:00:30,499
It concerns the effect of the combination
of velocities

7
00:00:30,499 --> 00:00:36,410
when a source moves with respect to the observer.
The wavelength of the emitted wave, it may

8
00:00:36,410 --> 00:00:41,080
be sound or light,
decreases if the source moves toward the observer,

9
00:00:41,080 --> 00:00:46,640
and thus we observe blueshift.
The wavelength increases if the source moves

10
00:00:46,640 --> 00:00:52,110
away from the observer,
in this case redshift is observed.

11
00:00:52,110 --> 00:00:58,460
One can see here a moving light source
and a representation of the perception of

12
00:00:58,460 --> 00:01:03,370
wavelength by the observer.
When the source moves forward, the wavelength

13
00:01:03,370 --> 00:01:07,190
is compressed
and the light seen by the observer is bluer.

14
00:01:07,190 --> 00:01:11,970
While moving in the opposite direction,
the wavelength increases and so it is seen

15
00:01:11,970 --> 00:01:14,670
redder,
redshift is observed.

16
00:01:14,670 --> 00:01:19,740
How does the Doppler effect work?
Considering at first a source at rest.

17
00:01:19,740 --> 00:01:24,630
It was just said that the Doppler effect is
due to the combination of movements,

18
00:01:24,630 --> 00:01:28,950
the combination of velocities,
so the velocity of wavelength propagation

19
00:01:28,950 --> 00:01:35,479
and the velocity of the emitting source.
Here we have a source at rest emitting a spherical

20
00:01:35,479 --> 00:01:38,880
wave
with some speed c

21
00:01:38,880 --> 00:01:45,479
and wavelength lambda zero (λ0).
λ0 is shown here,

22
00:01:45,479 --> 00:01:50,990
so wavelength is the pulsation of the wave.
In the case of the light, the velocity is

23
00:01:50,990 --> 00:01:57,710
equal to c.
Now, what is happening when the source moves?

24
00:01:57,710 --> 00:02:00,970
Here we have a wavefront that was emitted
at the time

25
00:02:00,970 --> 00:02:05,450
when the source was in this place.
The source will continue to emit the wavefronts

26
00:02:05,450 --> 00:02:11,009
while moving forward.
While this wavefront was emitted,

27
00:02:11,009 --> 00:02:18,379
this one was propagating, and so on.
Here we arrive at a situation

28
00:02:18,379 --> 00:02:22,480
in which the wavefronts were emitted in the
same way as when the source was at rest

29
00:02:22,480 --> 00:02:25,969
but are combined with the velocity of the
source.

30
00:02:25,969 --> 00:02:33,730
It can be noticed that the wavefronts are
closer to each other toward the observer

31
00:02:33,730 --> 00:02:36,340
and further from each other in the opposite
direction.

32
00:02:36,340 --> 00:02:42,829
How does it work?
Here the wavelengths will appear bluer

33
00:02:42,829 --> 00:02:46,719
and here redder.
Now, let's draw the axis representing the

34
00:02:46,719 --> 00:02:55,249
direction of the observer
and the source with some velocity v.

35
00:02:55,249 --> 00:03:03,020
Then, the source emits the wavefronts
so we can draw one here and another one over

36
00:03:03,020 --> 00:03:08,250
here.
Wavelength emitted by the source at rest,

37
00:03:08,250 --> 00:03:17,730
will be called λ0.
Now we consider Δt,

38
00:03:17,730 --> 00:03:22,329
the time interval between two wavefronts seen
by the observer.

39
00:03:22,329 --> 00:03:28,220
What will be this time interval?
Obviously, if the source is at rest Δt is

40
00:03:28,220 --> 00:03:31,809
equal to Δt0,
which is also the period of the wave.

41
00:03:31,809 --> 00:03:36,499
We can say that Δt0 is the period of the
wave,

42
00:03:36,499 --> 00:03:41,340
the period of the wave at rest.
The relation between those two time intervals

43
00:03:41,340 --> 00:03:48,129
is Δt = Δt0 if nothing moves.
But if the source is not at rest, during the

44
00:03:48,129 --> 00:03:56,309
time Δt0
it will move a given distance Δx

45
00:03:56,309 --> 00:04:01,370
continuously emitting wavefronts.
Finally, the time separating two wavefronts

46
00:04:01,370 --> 00:04:08,309
seen by the observer
will be equal to Δt0 minus another time interval

47
00:04:08,309 --> 00:04:12,730
that is equal to the time needed for the source
to move with the velocity v

48
00:04:12,730 --> 00:04:20,750
a distance Δx that is shown here.
Of course, the velocity of the wave is c.

49
00:04:20,750 --> 00:04:32,020
Now, one just has to rewrite Δx as vΔt0
which is the distance the source moved during

50
00:04:32,020 --> 00:04:36,680
the time that separates
two wavefronts at rest with the velocity v.

51
00:04:36,680 --> 00:04:42,270
Obviously, it is divided by c
as the wave is propagating with the speed

52
00:04:42,270 --> 00:04:45,819
of light
in the case of the electromagnetic waves.

53
00:04:45,819 --> 00:04:56,500
We also have that λ= cΔt,
so it suffices to divide the whole expression

54
00:04:56,500 --> 00:04:59,720
by c
to obtain that λ , the wavelength seen by

55
00:04:59,720 --> 00:05:08,870
the observer,
is λ minus v/c λ0.

56
00:05:08,870 --> 00:05:13,150
This is the expression for the Doppler effect
that combines the wavelength in the reference

57
00:05:13,150 --> 00:05:16,879
frame of the source,
so, what the source sees while emitting the

58
00:05:16,879 --> 00:05:19,659
wave,
and the wavelength seen by the observer.

59
00:05:19,659 --> 00:05:24,860
Here the case of the source moving toward
the observer was presented,

60
00:05:24,860 --> 00:05:29,560
but if the source moves away, the sign changes
here for +,

61
00:05:29,560 --> 00:05:34,740
so we would be in the situation where
the wave propagates in a direction opposite

62
00:05:34,740 --> 00:05:37,789
to the observer.
The expression for the Doppler effect can

63
00:05:37,789 --> 00:05:42,009
be written in several different ways.
In the previous slide it was written in this

64
00:05:42,009 --> 00:05:47,139
way.
The minus sign is due to the fact that,

65
00:05:47,139 --> 00:05:52,870
as was seen in the figure which was just drawn,
the source moves toward the observer.

66
00:05:52,870 --> 00:05:56,370
The plus sign appears if the source moves
away from the observer.

67
00:05:56,370 --> 00:05:59,129
It should be noted that
the sources do not always

68
00:05:59,129 --> 00:06:02,379
move in the same direction as the line of
sight to the observer.

69
00:06:02,379 --> 00:06:08,530
Let say the observer is in this place.
In one situation the source can go in the

70
00:06:08,530 --> 00:06:13,310
direction of the observer,
but there can also be the case in which the

71
00:06:13,310 --> 00:06:16,870
source moves in the other direction.
Let this be the velocity vector, the angle

72
00:06:16,870 --> 00:06:20,169
θ is the angle
between the line connecting the source with

73
00:06:20,169 --> 00:06:24,960
the observer and the velocity vector.
What counts in this case

74
00:06:24,960 --> 00:06:28,280
is the velocity of the source along the line
of sight -

75
00:06:28,280 --> 00:06:33,270
the velocity that is projected on the line
of sight.

76
00:06:33,270 --> 00:06:37,139
So in fact the full expression for the Doppler
effect

77
00:06:37,139 --> 00:06:45,940
Is Δλ/λ, or λ -λ0/λ0,
equals minus v over c times the cosine of

78
00:06:45,940 --> 00:06:49,550
the angle between the velocity vector
and the line of sight connecting the source

79
00:06:49,550 --> 00:06:54,319
to the observer.
Clearly, θ takes the values in the range

80
00:06:54,319 --> 00:07:03,949
from 0 to π.
The redshift is often written as z

81
00:07:03,949 --> 00:07:14,219
The redshift is often written as z
and relates for example to the cosmological

82
00:07:14,219 --> 00:07:18,470
redshift.
The expression for the Doppler effect can

83
00:07:18,470 --> 00:07:26,199
be written in more compact way
as λ = λ0 times (1 + z).

84
00:07:26,199 --> 00:07:29,889
If the velocity or the redshift of the source
is known,

85
00:07:29,889 --> 00:07:35,569
one can relate the observed wavelengths
to the wavelengths emitted by the source

86
00:07:35,569 --> 00:07:39,509
as if it was at rest.
We have already defined the redshift,

87
00:07:39,509 --> 00:07:41,919
but how in practice the redshift is measured
?

88
