00:19:12,860 --> 00:19:15,980
system.
Let's draw this situation.

217
00:19:15,980 --> 00:19:18,790
The important data can be obtained from the
star's spectra

218
00:19:18,790 --> 00:19:30,320
taken at regular intervals.
The velocity will be presented on the y axis,

219
00:19:30,320 --> 00:19:36,360
so v sin i, as a function of time.
This curve is called the velocity curve.

220
00:19:36,360 --> 00:19:40,680
Obviously, the stars in the Galaxy have some
velocity

221
00:19:40,680 --> 00:19:43,270
so we need to centre the axis on the mean
velocity

222
00:19:43,270 --> 00:19:51,320
of our star in the Galaxy.
This velocity is typically equal to some tens

223
00:19:51,320 --> 00:19:54,730
or hundreds of km/s.
The mean velocity

224
00:19:54,730 --> 00:19:59,240
can be represented
in this way

225
00:19:59,240 --> 00:20:03,130
with an arbitrary direction.
This vector represents the mean velocity of

226
00:20:03,130 --> 00:20:06,390
the star in the Galaxy,
so the velocity of the centre of mass of the

227
00:20:06,390 --> 00:20:10,230
system.
The star rotates about the centre of mass,

228
00:20:10,230 --> 00:20:16,450
and we can put the data coming from the different
positions on the diagram.

229
00:20:16,450 --> 00:20:23,580
Starting with position 1:
if the observer is here,

230
00:20:23,580 --> 00:20:30,461
there is no radial component of the velocity
and no change observed with respect to the

231
00:20:30,461 --> 00:20:34,559
mean velocity.
On the contrary, for position 2

232
00:20:34,559 --> 00:20:37,910
the velocity vector is radial with respect
to the observer,

233
00:20:37,910 --> 00:20:42,250
and a point corresponding to this position
can be placed here.

234
00:20:42,250 --> 00:20:47,420
This velocity is equal to v mean +v max sin
i .

235
00:20:47,420 --> 00:20:52,250
Position 3 corresponds to position 1,
with the difference that this point is obtained

236
00:20:52,250 --> 00:20:55,650
further in time.
As before, the velocity is equal to the mean

237
00:20:55,650 --> 00:20:58,940
velocity because of the lack of the radial
component.

238
00:20:58,940 --> 00:21:03,490
Position 4 is similar to position 2
but the velocity vector has the opposite direction

239
00:21:03,490 --> 00:21:06,690
so on the diagram the point should be placed
on the other side.

240
00:21:06,690 --> 00:21:13,870
The velocity in this case is equal to v mean
minus v max times the sine of the inclination.

241
00:21:13,870 --> 00:21:21,110
By connecting the points
we obtain the velocity curve

242
00:21:21,110 --> 00:21:26,850
which is obviously periodic.
So what we can measure directly is the rotation

243
00:21:26,850 --> 00:21:34,850
period
of the star around the centre of gravity

244
00:21:34,850 --> 00:21:38,770
which is equal to the rotation period of the
planet around the centre of gravity,

245
00:21:38,770 --> 00:21:41,550
as we are in the frame of the centre of mass
of the system.

246
00:21:41,550 --> 00:21:45,070
That kind of curve, the velocity curve of
a star, suffices

247
00:21:45,070 --> 00:21:49,840
to deduce the period of rotation of the planet
and the maximal velocity of the star rotating

248
00:21:49,840 --> 00:21:55,120
around the gravity centre.
This was another important application of

249
00:21:55,120 --> 00:22:00,060
the Doppler effect.
At last, the Hubble law, so we do now a drastic

250
00:22:00,060 --> 00:22:04,090
change in spatial scales
and enter into the domain of cosmology.

251
00:22:04,090 --> 00:22:10,040
As the Universe expands,
the distances between the galaxies,

252
00:22:10,040 --> 00:22:14,460
schematically presented in the figure,
will increase with time.

253
00:22:14,460 --> 00:22:19,930
Because of this expansion
so, after some time the galaxies have moved

254
00:22:19,930 --> 00:22:25,130
away from each other.
The metric expanded

255
00:22:25,130 --> 00:22:28,610
and all the arrows drawn here on the image
become larger.

256
00:22:28,610 --> 00:22:32,530
Due to the increased distances,
if the observer was placed in one of those

257
00:22:32,530 --> 00:22:35,530
galaxies
he/she would observe the other galaxies moving

258
00:22:35,530 --> 00:22:40,840
away.
The Hubble law

259
00:22:40,840 --> 00:22:43,380
relates the velocity of galaxies that move
away,

260
00:22:43,380 --> 00:22:47,910
this velocity being completely radial
with respect to the line of sight to each

261
00:22:47,910 --> 00:22:51,260
galaxy.
so the velocity of these galaxies is proportional

262
00:22:51,260 --> 00:22:56,030
to the distance between the galaxies.
These velocities of the galaxies are measured

263
00:22:56,030 --> 00:22:59,730
using the Doppler effect,
the distance, as it will be seen later, is

264
00:22:59,730 --> 00:23:03,860
measured with the distance modulus.
Then, the proportionality constant can be

265
00:23:03,860 --> 00:23:08,610
deduced.
As we have seen during this lecture,

266
00:23:08,610 --> 00:23:12,480
the Doppler-Fizeau effect has lots of applications
in astrophysics:

267
00:23:12,480 --> 00:23:16,870
from the search for exoplanets using velocity
curves

268
00:23:16,870 --> 00:23:23,460
of stars hosting planets,
to the rotation of stars

269
00:23:23,460 --> 00:23:26,450
and to the measurement of the temperature
of the interstellar medium,

270
00:23:26,450 --> 00:23:29,040
or to the measure of the rate of expansion
of the Universe

271
00:23:29,040 --> 00:23:34,010
using the recessional velocity of galaxies.
We will get back many times to the Doppler

272
00:23:34,010 --> 00:23:37,140
effect during this course.
It is worth mentioning that

273
00:23:37,140 --> 00:23:41,430
each time a theoretical model, an idea or
a concept predicts velocities,

274
00:23:41,430 --> 00:23:45,059
the practical way of measuring them will be
by using the Doppler effect.

